 Short version: pipy is a Python, local-first slopfork/experiment inspired by Pi; Pi in ~/src/pi-mono is the full TypeScript/Node product monorepo.

 Key differences:

 - Language / packaging
     - pipy: Python 3.11+, uv, version 0.1.0, no runtime deps declared.
     - pi-mono: TypeScript/Node monorepo, npm workspaces, version 0.75.5.
 - Project shape
     - pipy: pipy_harness + pipy_session.
     - pi: four main packages:
         - @earendil-works/pi-ai
         - @earendil-works/pi-agent-core
         - @earendil-works/pi-coding-agent
         - @earendil-works/pi-tui
 - Product maturity
     - pi: full public coding-agent harness with rich interactive TUI, npm install, docs, extensions, themes, skills, RPC, SDK.
     - pipy: local experimental/native runtime direction with conservative capture and a smaller line-oriented shell.
 - Session model
     - pi: stores full JSONL tree sessions under ~/.pi/agent/sessions, with /tree, /fork, /clone, compaction, resume, export/share.
     - pipy: stores metadata-first session records under ~/.local/state/pipy/sessions; raw transcripts are opt-in sidecars. It intentionally avoids archiving prompts, model text, tool payloads, diffs, secrets, etc.
 - UI
     - pi: real terminal UI: editor, footer, overlays, model selector, keybindings, image paste, message queues, extension UI.
     - pipy: Pi-like chrome and slash menu, but still mainly a line-oriented REPL. Full TUI/keybinding/editor parity is deferred.
 - Tools
     - pi: default model tools include read, write, edit, and bash.
     - pipy: has bounded read, ls, grep, find, write, edit, edit_diff, truncate; production bash is deliberately not registered until there is a real sandbox.
 - Providers
     - pi: much broader provider/model catalog, including subscriptions like Anthropic, OpenAI Codex, GitHub Copilot, plus many API-key providers.
     - pipy: smaller stdlib-only provider set: fake, OpenAI, OpenAI Codex, OpenAI chat completions, OpenRouter, Anthropic, Google, Vertex, Mistral, Bedrock, Azure OpenAI, Cloudflare.
 - Customization
     - pi: real extensions, skills, prompt templates, themes, and Pi packages.
     - pipy: discovers some analogous resources, but runtime extension/package loading is mostly deferred.
 - Integration modes
     - pi: interactive, print/JSON, RPC, SDK.
     - pipy: pipy, pipy repl, pipy run, subprocess capture, and a Python SDK boundary; network/RPC daemon is deferred.

 One nuance: docs/parity-criterion.md says pipy is 49/50 on its locked parity checklist, with only production bash missing. But that checklist explicitly excludes big Pi surfaces like the full TUI and extension/package
 ecosystem, so practical Pi feature parity is still not complete.

